Web Servers ::

Nginx and Apache are the two big web servers you'll run into. If the request is for something that doesn't change often, like CSS, JavaScript, or images, your Rails app probably doesn't need to see it. The web server can handle the request itself, without even talking to your app. It'll usually be faster that way.

......................................

Nginx and Apache are the two big web servers you'll run into. 

......................................

Whatâ€™s a web server?
A web server is a program that takes a request to your website from a user and does some processing on it. Then, it might give the request to your Rails app. Nginx and Apache are the two big web servers youâ€™ll run into.

If the request is for something that doesnâ€™t change often, like CSS, JavaScript, or images, your Rails app probably doesnâ€™t need to see it. The web server can handle the request itself, without even talking to your app. Itâ€™ll usually be faster that way.

Web servers can handle SSL requests, serve static files and assets, compress requests, and do lots of other things that almost every website needs. And if your Rails app does need to handle a request, the web server will pass it on to your app server.


......................................


Whatâ€™s an app server?
An app server is the thing that actually runs your Rails app. Your app server loads your code and keeps your app in memory. When your app server gets a request from your web server, it tells your Rails app about it. After your app is done handling the request, the app server sends the response back to the web server (and eventually to the user).

You can run most app servers by themselves, without a web server in front of it. Thatâ€™s probably what you do in development mode! In production, though, youâ€™ll usually have a web server in front. Itâ€™ll handle multiple apps at once, render your assets faster, and deal with a lot of the processing youâ€™ll do on every request.

There are a ton of app servers for Rails apps, including Mongrel (which isnâ€™t used much anymore), Unicorn, Thin, Rainbows, and Puma. Each has different advantages and different philosophies. But in the end, they all accomplish the same thing â€“ keeping your Rails app running and handling requests.


......................................

What is Passenger ??

Phusion Passenger is a little unique. In â€œstandalone mode,â€ it can act just like an app server. But it can also be built right into a web server, so you donâ€™t need a separate app server to run your Rails apps.

This can be really convenient. Especially if youâ€™re planning to run a bunch of apps and donâ€™t want to spend time setting up an app server for each one. After installing Passenger, you just point the web server directly at your Rails app (instead of an app server), and your Rails app will start handling requests!

Passenger is a nice option, but having a separate app server can be still be good. Keeping the app server separate gives you the flexibility to choose an app server that best fits your needs, and you can run and scale it on its own. Still, Iâ€™m going to try it again the next time I deploy a new small app. Iâ€™m hoping itâ€™ll make it easier to deploy future apps to the same server.

......................................

What about Rack?
Rack is the magic that lets any of these app servers run your Rails app. (Or Sinatra app, or Padrino app, orâ€¦)

You can think of Rack as a common language that Ruby web frameworks (like Rails) and app servers both speak. Because each side knows the same language, it means Rails can talk to Unicorn and Unicorn to Rails, without having either Rails or Unicorn know anything about the other.

